\begin_layout Standard
A Bayesian Network (BN) is statistical model that combines probability theory and graph theory.
 The underlying graph architecture comprises a set of nodes that represent an event or process that is undertaken,
 grouped together into a network,
 known as a directed,
 acyclic graph (DAG).
 A DAG depicts relationships by denoting nodes (also known as vertices) connected to each other with arcs known as edges.
 In a DAG,
 the edges have an explicitly stated direction of relationship and there is no feedback loop between any two vertices.
 Note should be taken that edges do not necessarily indicate causation in a BN 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Lemmer2013,BiedermanTaroni2012"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Often,
 vertices are described with a parent-child or sibling relationship.
 A depiction of a simple BN can be seen in Figure 
