\begin_layout Standard
BNs show an interesting characteristic that the state of a vertex is conditional only on the state of its parents and not the state of any other vertex in the network,
 a characteristic known as conditional independence.
 This characteristic enables a reduction in the number of factors that need to be incorporated into the joint probability calculation for scenarios.
 As computation power availability grows,
 more complex BNs can be developed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This architecture can be used to infer about a proposition by using the relationships to calculate the joint probability of the proposition across the nodes of the BN.
 This makes them ideal for scenario testing in forensic investigations 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Vlek2015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 DAGs are versatile constructs,
 not restricted to just forensic science.
 Ongoing use is common in many fields,
 including epidemiology 
