\begin_layout Section
Bayesian Networks in Forensics 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "chap:BNsInFornesics"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
BNs can be used to support the assessment of opposing propositions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Evett2002"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Information obtained from evidence is used to inform a framework of circumstances.
 utilise the hierarchy of propositions to guide the description of relationships between vertices 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Evett2002"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Bayesian Networks have been used in forensic science applications since the late 1980s 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "BiedermanTaroni2012"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Initially,
 as a means of investigating sub-source propositions such as the inference of profiles from mixed DNA samples,
 they began to be used to represent the relationships at higher levels as scientists found them to be a useful method of explaining the interaction of the pertinent evidence.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Concerns around the use of BNs in forensics include the subjectivity of the CPTs in networks assembled by different practitioners.
 Why certain publications were used,
 and Assessment of the network to determine the effect of the values used is important to ensure the evaluation is robust and limitations are understood 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Schaapveld2019,ChenPollino2012"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Although there have been many advancements in causal model algorithms in the field of artificial intelligence in recent years,
 there is a lag in the transparency or explainability of outputs derived from these complex models that makes them less attractive to a forensic or legal context.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As networks become more complex there has been a move to the use of object-oriented Bayesian Networks (OOBNs),
 which allow the embedding of sub-networks within the larger network.
\end_layout

